article.description:
Cheryl Ford had 24 points and 11
rebounds and Katie Smith added 20 points to help the Detroit Shock
beat the defending WNBA champion Sacramento Monarchs 91-71 on
Wednesday night.
article.headline: Ford's double-double helps Shock stun Monarchs
article.linkText: Ford's double-double helps Shock stun Monarchs
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Shock wanted to send a
message Wednesday night. They certainly were successful.

A year after being embarrassed twice by the Sacramento Monarchs,
the Shock got 24 points and 11 rebounds from Cheryl Ford and routed
the defending WNBA champions 91-71.

"This was a big win for us," said Deanna Nolan, who added 14
points for Detroit. "Because of who they are and what they did to
us last year."

The teams played twice last season, and the Monarchs won the
pair by an average of 28.5 points. The second game, in Sacramento,
finished 91-51.

"They whacked us pretty good last year," Shock coach Bill
Laimbeer said. "We talked about that this week, because we didn't
want to go there again. We look at them as a potential Finals
opponent, so we wanted this game badly."

The teams will play again Sunday in Sacramento.

"We just got whipped," Monarchs coach John Whisenant said.
"I've not coached a game in the WNBA where we've given up 90
points. We've got some problems on our defensive end."

Detroit (17-7) has won three in a row, while the Monarchs
(16-10) have lost two straight. Sacramento was 9-0 against the East
until losing its last two games to Indiana and Detroit.

"Right now, we're just not gelling," Sacramento's Yolanda
Griffith said. "We have to figure out a way to help this team
win."

Katie Smith added 20 points for Detroit, but it was Ford that
impressed Whisenant.

"She's the Mailman's daughter," he said, referring to Ford's
father, Hall of Famer Karl Malone. "Her dad was a blacksmith, and
I call her a blacksmith. Everything she touches, she hangs onto
with a Vise-Grips."

Detroit's Swin Cash left the game with 3:01 after falling to the
floor while the teams were lined up for a free throw.

"Cheryl hit me in the head while we were going for a rebound,"
Cash said. "It wasn't bad at first, but then I started seeing
black spots and I thought I was going to pass out. I'll be OK -- I
just have a horrible headache."

Nicole Powell led Sacramento with 14 points and Rebekkah Brunson
had 13 in the Monarchs' worst loss of the year.

The Shock scored the game's first seven points and shot 63.3
percent from the floor en route to a 50-41 halftime lead.

The Monarchs cut it to 54-52 in the third quarter, but Detroit
answered with an 12-3 run to take a 66-55 lead. Smith had a pair of
3-pointers in the surge.

Detroit had a 67-60 advantage at the end of the quarter, then
scored the first nine points of the fourth to put the game away.

"We called this a championship game," Laimbeer said. "This
was huge."
